title: For Sale:  200 1 oz 12 ga slugs for loading
postcontent:
I have 200 1 oz 12 Ga. slugs for loading your own at 20 cents each this is a fraction of the cost of commercial loaded 12 ga slug rounds. I have used the load data from the third one down in my Mossberg 500 with good results.

 These slugs were designed specifically for re-loaders. The diameter is sized .680" to allow the slug to be loaded into a standard plastic trap wad in place of the shot. While most commercial slug loads have a rolled crimp, the loads for this slug were developed for a conventional folded crimp on top of the shot shell. These really are as simple as replacing the shot with a slug and using the load data which is included with your order. Additional load data is also readily available on the internet. I suggest you try loading a few first to make sure they work to your satisfaction before loading a bunch of these. Occasionally, a combination of shot shell and wad will result in the wad being reluctant to separate from the slug, but an inexpensive piece of felt, paper or cardboard wad between the shot cup and the slug will prevent this problem. Or simply choose a different wad. Most of the time, this is not an issue at all.

The slug is loaded in a standard trap hull with standard wad and conventional folded crimp. Slug loads are produced with any shot shell reloading press. These slugs feature the exclusive drive key. The drive key is the horizontal tab shown inside the hollow base. It positively rotates the slug in rifled shotgun barrels. The key doubles as a support rib allowing use of a standard trap wad - no need for a support wad or base filler. The sabot wad design outperforms rifled slugs in rifled slug barrels. Velocity and accuracy meet or exceed expensive factory loaded rifled slugs. Even in smooth bore shotgun barrels, the accuracy is surprisingly good, and the smooth bore allows you to easily switch between shot and slug load

I will provide load data to whom ever buys these.

postcontent:
Used Noveske Gen2 chainsaw lower, complete minus stock. I would like to trade for a Romanian GP WASR-10/63.

A little about the lower: It is an older Gen2, so Gen3 PMAGs don't fit unless you alter the mag or the lower's mag well. The issue is the over-insertion tab on the back of the Gen3 PMAGs just barely don't fit because of the lower's flared mag well. You can force them in, but I wouldn't recommend it. All other mags are compatible as far as I know.

This lower used to be registered on a Form 4 as an SBR. However, since it is no longer in SBR configuration, it is treated like a normal lower. If you have questions reference the ATF website: https://www.atf.gov/firearms/faq/national-firearms-act-short-barreled-rifles-shotguns.html#receiver-sale

I had a professional gunsmith mill out the inside a little. It doesn't really change anything, just makes it the same dimensions inside as a select fire lower minus the hole needed for the full-auto sear. It doesn't change the legality.

The castle nut is not staked. The LPK is CMMG.

Please let me know if you have questions.
